es first, it could mess up our coverage and loading. Also, classes from Guice might trigger unwanted behavior before the actual test method is called. It's a lot to consider!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing class loading issues**\\n\\nI’m observing that the loading test class has a constant pool reference to `$FinalizableReferenceQueue` but doesn’t actually initialize it. There’s no indication that other JUnit tests could be affecting this either. I wonder if `Deny` can load the finalizer—probably not since the test method needs an initial call.\\n\\nI’m noting a potential issue with a separate test task using `forkEvery=1`, as the static initialization of the FRQ in the `SystemLoader` test could happen before the test via the class verifier. I need to make my final notes clear: I didn't run the tests myself, and that should be included in the concise summary.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented focused coverage for `com.google.inject.internal.util.$FinalizableReferenceQueue$SystemLoader`.\n\nChanges:\n- Added dedicated test file:\n  - `tests/src/com.google.inject/guice/3.0/src/test/java/com_google_inject/guice/InnerFinalizableReferenceQueueInnerSystemLoaderTest.java`\n- Updated the custom system class loader so the new SystemLoader-focused test allows `$Finalizer` to be loaded through the system loader, while existing tests can still force the decoupled loader path.\n- Set `forkEvery = 1` for JVM tests in:\n  - `tests/src/com.google.inject/guice/3.0/build.gradle`\n\nThis ensures `$FinalizableReferenceQueue` initializes independently per test class, allowing both the existing decoupled-loader coverage and the new system-loader coverage to be exercised.\n\nTests were not run, per instruction.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0b76f827bfda5ac60169fa7264bbe081a1a01fcdc311ce9832\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 674, "output": 660, "cacheRead": 286